<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<chapter xml:id="ch-orthogonality" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Orthogonality</title>

<introduction>
<p>
  Learning goals:
  <ul>
    <li>
      Know how to check if two vectors are orthogonal.
    </li>
    <li>
      Know how to find the coefficients of a linear combination using an orthogonal/orthonormal basis.
    </li>
    <li>
      Be able to build an orthonormal basis given an orthogonal basis.
    </li>
    <li>
      Define the orthogonal complement of a subspace of <m>\R^n</m>.
    </li>
    <li>
      Given an orthogonal set and a vector, use the formula from the orthogonal lemma to construct a larger orthogonal set.
    </li>
    <li>
      Use the Gram-Schmidt process to find an orthogonal basis for a given subspace of <m>\R^n</m>.
    </li>
    <li>
      Find the orthogonal complement of a subspace spanned by a given set of vectors.
    </li>
    <li>
      Find the projection of a vector onto a given subspace.
    </li>
    <li>
      Find the point in a plane closest to a given point.
    </li>
    <li>
      Find a basis for the orthogonal complement of a given subspace.
    </li>
    <li>
      Determine if a given matrix is orthogonal.
    </li>
    <li>
      Normalize the rows or columns of a matrix to produce an orthogonal matrix.
    </li>
    <li>
      Explain why orthogonal matrices are easy to invert.
    </li>
    <li>
      Verify properties of matrices in a QR-factorization (orthonormality of <m>Q</m>, upper triangularity of <m>R</m>).
    </li>
    <li>
      Compute the QR-factorization of a matrix with linearly independent columns.
    </li>
    <li>
      Understand the relationship between QR-factorization and the Gram-Schmidt process.
    </li>
    <li>
      Solve linear systems using QR-factorization.
    </li>
  </ul>
</p>  
</introduction>

